dismissalText.commentary: Hasan Ali c du Plessis b Phehlukwayo 59 (45b 5x4 3x6 55m) SR: 131.11

dismissalComment.html: what a catch! Faf du Plessis pulls off an outstanding catch at long on to close out the innings. Hasan cleared his front leg and aimed for the top tier, but he didn't get all of it. Du Plessis tracked the ball from wide long on, running round while maintaining his distance from the boundary marker, and finally timing his leap to perfection to pluck the ball out of the air. That was six if he'd missed it, but du Plessis holds on and Phehlukwayo ends the innings with a career best 4 for 22

dismissalText.commentary: Imam-ul-Haq c Phehlukwayo b Rabada 5 (14b 0x4 0x6 19m) SR: 35.71

dismissalComment.html: a pull, a top edge, and a simple catch! Rabada dug this one in to surprise Imam, who was camped on the front foot. He rocked back on the pull, but not quickly enough to control the stroke. The ball loops tamely to midwicket, where Phehlukwayo holds a simple chance. That was a wonderfully set-up wicket from Rabada, who drew Imam further and further forward before mixing it up with a short one on a pitch that is not quick, but has shown appreciable bounce

dismissalComment.html: once again the short ball does the trick! Rabada digs it in, Babar steps back to pull but the ball balloons off the top edge as he's much too early into the shot. Again it's Phehlukwayo who holds the catch, but this time he's running in from the midwicket boundary. Two bouncers have brought two wickets, and Pakistan are re-living some of their troubles from the Test series. And Olivier hasn't even bowled yet!

commentTextItems.html: short and rising on middle stump, and van der Dussen rocks back to hammer a pull through midiwcket and seal a five-wicket win

commentPostTextItems.html: What a start to one-day international cricket van der Dussen has had - 93 on debut, and now a match-winning 80* as South Africa win by five wickets. And he couldn't have done it without Andile Phehlukwayo's career best 69 not out. Given his efforts with the ball earlier, he's a good shout for Player of the Match. Together they put on 127 - which is a record for the sixth wicket at this ground, and not too far off South Africa's best ever. It was enough to overcome Pakistan, despite the early strikes from Afridi and Shadab, and despite the fight shown with the bat by Hasan Ali and Sarfraz Ahmed earlier.

"We didn't get a good start, and we gave away too many soft wickets. Hasan Ali batted really well and put some hope into the team. We had a chance when we had them 80 for 5, but Phehlukwayo and the other batsman batted really well," says Sarfraz Ahmed.

"I've got a role to play," says Man of the Match Andile Phehlukwayo. "If you hit the deck hard, there was a bit in there. I was a bit nervous to begin with when I batted. Rassie did a good job of calming me down. I stuck to my plans and played with intensity. There was some good chat. Shadab was one of the hardest to pick. At the end of the day, it was good cricket. I'm a positive person, I really like scoring boundaries and making runs."

"What you're looking for in a situation like that from two young guys is to learn a lot," says winning captain Faf du Plessis. "To get through an innings like that will give them a lot. Andile is playing for that no. 7 slot so this was a big innings. In a perfect world, we should have chased 140 or 150, so it was a bit too many. An amazing start to his international career for Rassie. What you look for in new players is composure and calmness at the crease. Tonight was a bit like playing in the subcontinent, hopefully we'll get a bit of pace in the next pitch. Dale will be back, and so will Quinny. But the great thing about this game was two guys taking their opportunity."
Mamunur Akand: "Where does this stand in top 6th wicket partnerships that finished a chase?" -- It's the second highest ever for SA, and it's 12th on this list
And that's all from your commentary team tonight. Join us again on Friday for the third ODI, which is another day/night affair at SuperSport Park in Centurion. Until then, goodbye!

Naveed: "Both teams had nervy moments- Pakistan at 112/8, while SA at 80/5. Both fought back from these low points but SA also had 2 new batters at crease. Credit to them, against a good bowling attack, they won with comfort at the end. So series is tied, making it more interesting. "
Zaheer Ahmed: "Faheem/Talat to be dropped for Amir/Imad in next for sure. It's smelling Dears"

dismissalText.commentary: David Miller c Imam-ul-Haq b Shadab Khan 31 (26b 5x4 0x6 37m) SR: 119.23

dismissalComment.html: Shadab strikes straight away! Miller was drawn in by the flight, and suckered by the slowness of the pitch as he flicked too early to leg, presenting short midwicket with an easy catch. Imam holds the catch, and it's a mirror of Hafeez' dismissal in the first innings

dismissalText.commentary: Heinrich Klaasen b Shadab Khan 0 (1b 0x4 0x6 3m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: two wickets in two balls for Shadab! He sends Klaasen back for a duck. Wrong'un, fizzes off the pitch and breaches the weak defences of Klaasen. The batsman sits back in the crease, he misjudges the length, and misses the ball altogether. Shadab is mobbed by his team-mates
